<HEAD>Air Force Jet Fighter Crashes Near Lake Okeechobee</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AVON PARK, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pilot of an F-16a fighter jet ejected
safely Wednesday before his plane crashed in a sparsely populated
area north of Lake Okeechobee, authorities said.
   First Lt. Mark Pugh, 27, of Belpre, Ohio, ejected when his
fighter went down during a training mission at the Avon Park Range
near here, Sgt. Tony Rowland, public affairs officer for the base.
   Pugh, attached to the 308th Tactical Fighter squadron at
Homestead Air Force Base, was not seriously injured and taken to
MacDill Air Force Base Hospital for observation.
   Crews from Homestead were dispatched to the crash site after the
mishap, which occurred about 10 a.m., Rowland said. He added that
there was no preliminary indication of what caused the $13.9 million
jet to go down.
   An accident board will investigate the accident, the spokesman
said.
